			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">addendum: cpu says windows code such as IsValidPointer (sp?) relies on the ability of nt.dll to handle exceptions, and probably occurs in normal system code paths.  thus, such a patch would have to determine whether we are executing in trusted context or not -- this should be easy by open-coding TLS access to a trusted-side variable that's modified in the trusted &lt;-&gt; untrusted context switch -- and letting the normal code path execute when we're executing trusted code, but generating a double fault when we're executing untrusted code.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-04-10T00:23:21.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-04-10T00:23:21.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 2 by b...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=1633#c2" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/1633/comments/full/2" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>